- VSCode Version: 1.6.1
- OS Version: Windows 10 1607 (14393.321)

Steps to Reproduce:

I can't give you a repro until we update the PowerShell extension and release it.  But I can describe what is going on.  I open a file with lots of functions in it.  I want to see the list of symbols so I press `Ctrl+Shift+O`.  I see this VSCode/extension exchange in our log:

```
    READ MESSAGE:

    {
      "jsonrpc": "2.0",
      "id": 4,
      "method": "textDocument/documentSymbol",
      "params": {
        "uri": "file:///c%3A/Users/Keith/GitHub/PowerShell/Plaster/src/InvokePlaster.ps1"
      }
    }

    WRITE MESSAGE:

    {
      "jsonrpc": "2.0",
      "id": "4",
      "result": [
        {
          "name": "AreFilesIdentical { }",
          "kind": 12,
          "location": {
            "uri": "c:/Users/Keith/GitHub/PowerShell/Plaster/src/InvokePlaster.ps1",
            "range": {
              "start": {
                "line": 647,
                "character": 8
              },
              "end": {
                "line": 659,
                "character": 9
              }
            }
          },
          "containerName": "InvokePlaster"
        },
        {
          "name": "ColorForOperation { }",
          "kind": 12,
          "location": {
            "uri": "c:/Users/Keith/GitHub/PowerShell/Plaster/src/InvokePlaster.ps1",
            "range": {
              "start": {
                "line": 1228,
                "character": 0
              },
              "end": {
                "line": 1240,
                "character": 1
              }
            }
          },
          "containerName": "InvokePlaster"
        },
        {
          "name": "ConvertToDestinationRelativePath { }",
          "kind": 12,
          "location": {
            "uri": "c:/Users/Keith/GitHub/PowerShell/Plaster/src/InvokePlaster.ps1",
            "range": {
              "start": {
                "line": 1179,
                "character": 0
              },
              "end": {
                "line": 1191,
                "character": 1
              }
            }
          },
          "containerName": "InvokePlaster"
        },
```

Note that I have updated the PowerShell extension to return Symbols in sorted order (by name).  Yet this is what VSCode shows in the UI:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5177512/19630545/e76fd3a0-9949-11e6-986c-40d81ab31e9a.png)

It appears to me that VSCode is trying to preserve the symbol order based on the position of the symbol in the file.  VSCode should really honor the order returned by the extension.  For instance, when I'm searching for a particular function, I couldn't give a flying flip about the relative position of the symbol in the file.  As we learned in Algorithms 101, searching a **SORTED** list is a helluva lot quicker than an unsorted list.  :-)

Please provide a way for symbols to be displayed in the order the extension supplies them to VSCode.

It seems at times that conflicting keys are not reported. Stepping through the code and adding some logs, I see the below.

**Command:**
Conflicts with `editor.action.selectHighlights` (https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/editor/contrib/find/common/findController.ts#L720).

``` javascript
registerCommand(new CoreCommand({
    id: H.TextLowerCase,
    precondition: ContextKeyExpr.and(EditorContextKeys.Writable, EditorContextKeys.HasNonEmptySelection),
    kbOpts: {
        weight: CORE_WEIGHT,
        // kbExpr: EditorContextKeys.TextFocus,
        kbExpr: null,
        primary: KeyMod.CtrlCmd | KeyMod.Shift | KeyCode.KEY_L
    }
}));
```

**findController.ts:**

``` javascript
@editorAction
export class SelectHighlightsAction extends AbstractSelectHighlightsAction {
    constructor() {
        super({
            id: 'editor.action.selectHighlights',
            label: nls.localize('selectAllOccurencesOfFindMatch', "Select All Occurences of Find Match"),
            alias: 'Select All Occurences of Find Match',
            precondition: null,
            kbOpts: {
                kbExpr: EditorContextKeys.Focus,
                primary: KeyMod.CtrlCmd | KeyMod.Shift | KeyCode.KEY_L
            }
        });
    }
}
```

**Debugging:**
1. It seems like this, https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/platform/keybinding/common/keybindingResolver.ts#L187, condition needs to be relaxed a bit. In the new command above, `kbExpr` is not present so this check fails resulting in no warning.
2. I haven't got to the reason why on a clean build the warning is issued, whilst at other times it isn't.
